window.docContents[142].resolve({"/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean":{"contents":"This blueprint is an atlas of formalised number theory in Lean: it collects the main, Wikipedia-level results of number theory as they exist in Lean today and weaves them into a single cross-project dependency graph spanning the ten principal areas below.\n\nWhat it covers. Three layers, distinguished on each node:\n\n* mathlib's number-theory core — live-checked against mathlib, so each result's completion status (sorry-free or in progress) is computed directly from Lean and shown by the node's colour in the dependency graph.* External Lean projects — results formalised in dedicated repositories (Fermat's Last Theorem and regular primes, modular forms and Hecke operators, the Chebotarev density theorem, the prime number theorem, adic spaces, class field theory, the polynomial Freiman–Ruzsa theorem, and more). These appear as informal nodes that link to the project formalising them, marked sorry-free or in progress according to that project's state.* Forthcoming in mathlib — results currently under review as open mathlib pull requests, each linked to its PR, so the atlas shows the moving frontier as well as the settled theory.\n\nHow to read it. The dependency graph at the foot of this page is the heart of the atlas: each node is a definition, theorem, or lemma, and an edge from  to  means  depends on . Node colour encodes completion status. Following an edge across a chapter boundary reveals the connections — how cyclotomic field theory feeds Fermat's Last Theorem for regular primes, or how the modular discriminant links modular forms to elliptic curves.\n\nA few cross-project chains worth tracing.\n\n* Regular primes: mathlib's cyclotomic fields → Kummer's criterion and Bernoulli numbers (flt-regular-bernoulli, KummerCriterion) → Fermat's Last Theorem for regular primes (flt-regular).* Modular forms: mathlib's modular forms and the slash action → the valence formula and strong multiplicity one (LeanModularForms) → the L-series of a modular form (forthcoming in mathlib).* Curves over finite fields: the elliptic-curve group law (mathlib) → the Hasse bound (Hasse-Weil) → the Weil conjectures.* Analytic core: the Riemann zeta and Dirichlet L-functions (mathlib) → non-vanishing on the line  (DirichletNonvanishing) → the prime number theorem and sieve methods (PNT+).\n\nThe ten chapters follow, each pairing every result with a human-readable statement and a paragraph-level proof sketch.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"","header":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean","id":"/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean"},"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Finiteness-of-the-class-group/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Finiteness-of-the-class-group--The-Class-Number":{"contents":"The class number  of a number field  is the cardinality of its (finite) class group\n():\n\nThus  precisely when  is a principal ideal domain, and the size of\n measures the failure of unique factorisation of elements in .\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory\u0009Finiteness of the class group","header":"3.7.2. The Class Number","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Finiteness-of-the-class-group/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Finiteness-of-the-class-group--The-Class-Number"},"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Prime-Number-Theorem-with-error-term___-and-Chebyshev-and-Mertens-asymptotics/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Prime-Number-Theorem-with-error-term___-and-Chebyshev-and-Mertens-asymptotics--Chebyshev-asymptotic-and-the-prime-counting-function":{"contents":"(Chebyshev asymptotic.) The first Chebyshev function () is asymptotic\nto the identity:\n\nEquivalently . This strengthens the elementary two-sided bounds\n() to a genuine asymptotic.\nFormalised in PrimeNumberTheoremAnd: chebyshev_asymptotic — sorry-free.\n\nThis is a consequence of the Prime Number Theorem (). Since  and\n differ only by the higher prime powers, \n(Chebyshev.abs_psi_sub_theta_le_sqrt_mul_log, the same mathlib bound used for\n), so  transfers to . The\nprime-counting form  then follows by partial summation, integrating\n against  (the identity Chebyshev.primeCounting_eq_theta_div_log_add_integral).\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Analytic Number Theory\u0009The Prime Number Theorem with error term, and Chebyshev and Mertens asymptotics","header":"2.11.2. Chebyshev asymptotic and the prime-counting function","id":"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Prime-Number-Theorem-with-error-term___-and-Chebyshev-and-Mertens-asymptotics/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Prime-Number-Theorem-with-error-term___-and-Chebyshev-and-Mertens-asymptotics--Chebyshev-asymptotic-and-the-prime-counting-function"},"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Decomposition-and-inertia-in-Galois-extensions/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Decomposition-and-inertia-in-Galois-extensions--Transitivity-of-the-Galois-Action-on-Primes":{"contents":"Let  be a finite Galois group for  and let  be primes of\n lying over the same prime  of . Then some  carries\n to ; equivalently,  acts transitively on the set of primes of\n over .\n\nThis is the ring-theoretic transitivity packaged in mathlib's invariant-theory layer: two primes\nof  with the same contraction to  are related by an element of any Galois group, the\nstatement IsInvariant.exists_smul_of_under_eq. The hypothesis  is exactly the \"same prime below\" condition, and the conclusion produces the\nrequired . Transitivity of the induced action on the finite set of primes over\n is the immediate consequence used throughout the rest of the section.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Class Field Theory and Galois Theory\u0009Decomposition and inertia in Galois extensions","header":"4.2.2. Transitivity of the Galois Action on Primes","id":"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Decomposition-and-inertia-in-Galois-extensions/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Decomposition-and-inertia-in-Galois-extensions--Transitivity-of-the-Galois-Action-on-Primes"}});